16 WHEREAS, thousands of Laotians braved the treacherous waters of the Mekong River to
17 seek refuge in Thailand, where they endured difficult conditions in overcrowded and
18 under-resourced refugee camps before being resettled in countries such as the United States;
19 and
20 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia extended a warm welcome to these Laotian refugees, with
21 vibrant communities forming in cities such as Atlanta, Cornelia, Chickamauga,
22 Lawrenceville, Marietta, Riverdale, and Macon, where they have worked diligently to
23 integrate into American society while preserving their cultural identity; and
24 WHEREAS, Laotian Americans in Georgia have made invaluable contributions to the state's
25 cultural and economic landscape, establishing businesses, cultural organizations, and
26 community centers that promote their heritage and foster a sense of belonging; and
27 WHEREAS, featuring a white three-headed elephant against a red background, the Airavata
28 flag holds profound cultural and historical significance for the Laotian community,
29 symbolizing the ancient Kingdom of Lan Xang, also known as the "Land of a Million
30 Elephants," which was one of the most prosperous kingdoms in Southeast Asia from the 14th
31 to the 18th centuries; and
32 WHEREAS, for Laotians living abroad, the Airavata flag serves as a powerful connection
33 to their history, identity, and traditions, representing unity, resilience, and the enduring spirit
34 of their ancestors; and
35 WHEREAS, it is abundantly fitting and proper that the Airavata flag be recognized as a
36 symbol of the Laotian American community, celebrating their journey, resilience, and
37 contributions to the diverse fabric of this state and the nation.
